sentences: Cora "Lovie" Austin (September 19, 1887 – July 8, 1972) was an American Chicago bandleader, session musician, composer, singer, and arranger during the 1920s classic blues era.
In 1923, Lovie Austin decided to make Chicago her home, and she lived and worked there for the rest of her life.
Singer Bessie Smith turned the song into a hit in 1923.
Austin and the Blues Serenaders recorded with Paramount Records during their temporary shift from New York to Chicago in 1923.
In 1961 as interest in her early career grew she made a significant recording with Alberta Hunter in Chicago.
Austin died on July 8, 1972 in Chicago.

When the classic blues craze began to wane in the early 1930s, Austin settled into the position of musical director for the Monogram Theater, at 3453 South State Street in Chicago where all the T.O.B.A. acts played.
Austin worked with many other top jazz musicians of the 1920s, including Louis Armstrong, with whom she worked on the song "Heebie Jeebies".
